h3. Summary
When installing Bitbucket from the ZIP archive in Windows, the services won't be automatically created as expected. To create the services, one must go over the instructions of the article below, however it's not possible to create the Elasticsearch service in windows, since the batch file responsible for creating the service is checking the wrong location.

https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucketserver/running-bitbucket-server-as-a-windows-service-776640048.html/

h3. How to Replicate

# Download the ZIP archive for [Bibtucket 5.9.1|https://www.atlassian.com/software/stash/downloads/binary/atlassian-bitbucket-5.9.0.zip]
# Install it;
# Go over the [Running Bitbucket Server as a Windows service|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucketserver/running-bitbucket-server-as-a-windows-service-776640048.html] to create the services;
# At step 9 change directory as instructed;
# At step 10 run the command below to create the Elasticsearch service
{code}
service.bat install MyName
{code}
# This will result in the following message:

h3. Expected Results
Elasticsearch service must be created

h3. Actual Results

After running the {code}service.bat install MyName{code} the following message will be shown and the service won't be created

{noformat}
FINDSTR: Cannot open <BBitbucket Server installation directory>\elasticsearch\config\jvm.options
{noformat}
 
h3. Notes
What is causing the issue is that the {{<Bitbucket Server installation directory>\elasticsearch\bin\service.bat}} is pointing to the wrong location while trying to find the {{jvm-options}} file.

In the batch file we can see the following

{code}
:foundJVM
if "%ES_JVM_OPTIONS%" == "" (
set ES_JVM_OPTIONS=%ES_HOME%\config\jvm.options
)
{code}

In the code above we can see that it is trying to check for the file in {{%ES_HOME%\config\}} however, there's no {{config}} folder but {{config-template}}.

h3.Workaround
# Edit the {{<Bitbucket Server installation directory>\elasticsearch\bin\service.bat}}
# replace {code}
:foundJVM
if "%ES_JVM_OPTIONS%" == "" (
set ES_JVM_OPTIONS=%ES_HOME%\config\jvm.options
)
{code}
# For {code}
:foundJVM
if "%ES_JVM_OPTIONS%" == "" (
set ES_JVM_OPTIONS=%ES_HOME%\config-template\jvm.options
)
{code}
# run the command in the step 10 of the article again;

h4. Summary
Ruby syntax in Bitbucket Server where the *heredoc* is not functioning properly correctly for its syntax highlighting. The following types of *Here Documents* are not functioning properly:
* {code:java|title=indent}
  expected_result = <<-INDENTED_HEREDOC
This would contain specially formatted text.

That might span many lines
  INDENTED_HEREDOC
{code}
* {code:java|title=squiggly}
expected_result = <<~SQUIGGLY_HEREDOC
  This would contain specially formatted text.

  That might span many lines
SQUIGGLY_HEREDOC
{code}
* {code:java|title=single quotes}
expected_result = <<-'EXPECTED'
One plus one is #{1 + 1}
EXPECTED
{code}
* {code:java|title=double quotes}
puts <<-"HEREDOC"
cat #{__FILE__}
HEREDOC
{code}
* {code:java|title=backticks}
puts <<-`HEREDOC`
cat #{__FILE__}
HEREDOC
{code}

h4. Steps to Reproduce
# In the local repository, write *poly.rb* ruby script.
# Make the commit and push to the remote repository.
# View the file in the *Source View* page.

h4. Expected Results
Bitbucket Server's source view page able to recognize the *heredoc* syntax and comment out/block out the content in between the *heredoc*.

h4. Actual Results.
Bitbucket Server's source view page unable to recognize the *heredoc* syntax.

h4. Workaround
Only the following *heredoc* syntax is recognized:
{code:java}
expected_result = <<HEREDOC
This would contain specially formatted text.

That might span many lines
HEREDOC
{code}
(i) The heredoc starts on the line following <<HEREDOC and ends with the next line that starts with HEREDOC. The result includes the ending newline.

h3. More information
The syntax information was referred at - http://ruby-doc.org/core-2.3.0/doc/syntax/literals_rdoc.html#label-Here+Documents

h3. Summary:

When PUBLIC level access is granted at Project permissions level, the public access for all repos in the project are getting inherited from the project permissions and applied to all repositories under the project -- so the repos in the project should be public.

However, when using the following REST call on a repository which is part of the project: {{GET /rest/projects/{projectKey}/repos}}, here is an example response from the call:

{noformat}{
    "slug": "justbecauseican",
    "id": 2,
    "name": "justbecauseican",
    "scmId": "git",
    "state": "AVAILABLE",
    "statusMessage": "Available",
    "forkable": true,
    "project": {
        "key": "PRO1",
        "id": 1,
        "name": "Project 1",
        "public": true,
        "type": "NORMAL",
        "links": {
            "self": [{
                "href": "http://localhost:7990/projects/PRO1"
            }]
        }
    },
    "public": false,
    "links": {
        "clone": [{
            "href": "ssh://git@localhost:7999/pro1/justbecauseican.git",
            "name": "ssh"
        }, {
            "href": "http://admin@localhost:7990/scm/pro1/justbecauseican.git",
            "name": "http"
        }],
        "self": [{
            "href": "http://localhost:7990/projects/PRO1/repos/justbecauseican/browse"
        }]
    }
}{noformat}

Note the {{"public": false,}} on the response.

As the repo is under a project which has public access set on the projects permissions, the repo should inherit the public access as well, so on the REST API response, it should be  {{"public": true}}

As can be seen at [Event payload|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucketserver/event-payload-938025882.html], currently just the repository slug is included. For example:
{noformat}
{ 
   "eventKey":"repo:refs_changed",
   "date":"2018-03-09T08:47:18-0500",
   "actor":{ 
      "name":"fkraemer",
      "emailAddress":"fkraemer@atlassian.com",
      "id":1,
      "displayName":"Felipe Kraemer",
      "active":true,
      "slug":"fkraemer",
      "type":"NORMAL"
   },
   "repository":{ 
      "slug":"testing",
      "id":1,
      "name":"Testing",
      "scmId":"git",
      "state":"AVAILABLE",
      "statusMessage":"Available",
      "forkable":true,
      "project":{ 
         "key":"TST",
         "id":1,
         "name":"Testing Project",
         "description":"This project is created for testing",
         "public":false,
         "type":"NORMAL"
      },
      "public":false
   },
   "changes":[ 
      { 
         "ref":{ 
            "id":"refs/heads/feature/Feature_PR",
            "displayId":"feature/Feature_PR",
            "type":"BRANCH"
         },
         "refId":"refs/heads/feature/Feature_PR",
         "fromHash":"e3ad5d4be86451c108562c5433cb49052adedd56",
         "toHash":"931e392f307dc1dbc110dd6dc974fba6381ac30b",
         "type":"UPDATE"
      }
   ]
}
{noformat}

h3. Suggestion
The payload should include the full repository URL (not just the repository name), i.e., {{"https://localhost:7990/scm/TST/testing.git"}} instead of just {{"testing"}}.

For instance, the Bitbucket Cloud [Event Payloads \- Repository|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/event-payloads-740262817.html#EventPayloads-entity_repository] (expanding the "Repository Property" section) includes repository full URL.
